            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Generally a good thing to have, although it always takes a serious amount of work to settle the ton of false positives that these tools throw at you when you first start them up. The output of your test run is full of those.\r\n\r\nNote that that service pretty much only runs pylint, pyflake, etc. These are best set up locally, for various reasons: being able to run them locally, being independent of specific service providers, allowing their use as a git commit-hook, etc.\r\n\r\nOur test runner in `runtests.py` already runs `pycodestyle` and adds the output to the test results. That's one way of doing it, certainly not the worst, athough there are other ways. If you want to start writing up configurations for pyflakes, pylint & friends, preferably starting from some reasonable base configuration, I'd be happy to get a PR for it.",
